--> According to the MAST people, you can have 4 320x200 24 bit
--> screens, two 320x400 or two 640x200 screens, or one 640x400
--> screen. Presumably this includes overscan, though the MAST person
--> we talked to specifically said 640 and 320... that may have been
--> just a general number. Here is where we begin to realize that any
--> "animation" will be very limited - you won't be able to update
--> a full resolution frame at all, as it takes all the memory. Any
--> animation requires that the data be completely pre-loaded into the
--> colorburst first, and then animated, because it takes multiple
--> Amiga frames to load the display memory on the colorburst hardware.
--> That's not mentioned in here, so we'll mention it: The way that this
--> device works is the Amiga's display is changed multiple times, up to
--> six completely different fields of information, to load ONE frame in
--> the colorburst hardware. So as it loads, you see the various R, G and
--> B portions of the image update. No way this can be updated in real
--> time over large portions of the image from the Amiga - that's why
--> any animation has to be pre-loaded into the colorburst first.
--> If we discount any time taken for disk loading and assume that the
--> data that is to be loaded into the colorburst can be sent as fast
--> as the six field technique can run, you can update ten frames per
--> second into the colorburst. Assuming that the colorburst is not in
--> high resolution, we presume you could double-buffer the load so that
--> you would not see the load (and the artifacts) occur. Contrast this
--> to the HAM-E animation rate - given the same conditions, that is,
--> animation data in memory, you can achieve and sustain 60 frames
--> per second as long as you have the memory available (which of
--> course depends on your Amiga's memory configuration) with no
--> artifacting at all.

ColorBurst's Video Coprocessor makes many realtime video special effects
possible, including:

* Continuous scrolling in 24 bits (for video titling and games)
---------------------------------------------------------------
--> We can do the same thing using the Amiga's custom chips;
--> The main difference is that our scrolling can be as large as the
--> Amiga's chip memory w/o any processor activity; the colorburst has
--> to be updated (by custom hardware specific software) for each
--> scan line that scrolls off beyond the 1.5 MB limit of the hardware.
--> We can scroll 9 MB without any particular operation beyond moving
--> data from fast to chip ram, and up to two megs w/o moving anything
--> in an a3000. Also, our scrolling is implemented by calling standard
--> Amiga system scroll routines, while the colorburst's scrolling will
--> have to be done by custom software drivers.

