--> At this point in the discussion, we would like to make a few points
--> of our own. While 24 bits is enormously different from 12 bits, to the
--> degree that the difference is obvious and generally causes first-time
--> viewers to say things like "wow!", the difference between a pure 24 bit
--> display and an 18 bit display which has been rendered by our software
--> is next to undetectable to the naked eye. Your eye is very near it's
--> limits of perception at 18 bits/pixel; You can only pick up differences
--> that subtle if the areas of color are large and adjacent to each other.
--> Our software can prevent that from happening, using extremely subtle
--> dither techniques to prevent it. If you put a colorburst and a HAM-E next
--> to each other, odds are you'll never see a difference in display
--> quality. Also our register mode is pure 24 bit; The issue never arises
--> for that mode. The MAST people say in this document that their
--> product has "far superior shading to any HAM card available." This
--> is marketing hype, no more and no less and you should treat it as
--> a nonsense claim. Technically, they have 256 grey shade output, and so
--> does the HAM-E. In our 18 bit HAM mode, using the special display
--> techniques provided in our renderer the display quality is
--> so nearly identical it's pointless to look for differences. For your
--> reference, the Amiga offers 16 levels per RGB gun stock, the HAM-E
--> provides both 64 and 256 levels per RGB gun, and the MAST device
--> provides 256 levels per RGB gun.
--> 
--> Price is an interesting issue. The hardware, advertising costs,
--> FCC approval, 1.5 megs of on board memory, connecting cable(s?),
--> (presumably) royalties to the MegaPaint people, and dealer margins
--> all eat into the stated $499.00 price with a vengance. We're not
--> saying they can't do it - we think they can, but the margins will
--> be very tight if they stick to this price. MAST has indicated
--> that they are working on custom silicon to some extent; this will
--> reduce production costs if they complete this effort. The HAM-E
--> attains it's low price point because it contains no memory other
--> than palette registers.
-->
--> To sum up, we know that the colorburst will be able to display very 
--> beautiful still images, in full 24 bit frames, just as we can. We know
--> that the colorburst's animation capabilities are very limited (by it's
--> local memory and slow Amiga to ColorBurst data transfer rate), unlike
--> the HAM-E's animation capabilities, which are only limited by Amiga
--> memory. We know that the colorburst can perform a pseudo-genlock
